  "prompt": "Are there statutes that address money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several statutes that address money laundering in the United States:\n\n1. Federal Statutes:\n- Bank Secrecy Act (BSA)\n- Money Laundering Control Act of 1986\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1956 (Money Laundering)\n- Title 18 U.S. Code Section 1957 (Monetary Transactions)\n- USA PATRIOT Act\n\n2. State Statutes:\n- Many states have their own money laundering laws that complement federal statutes\n- These often mirror federal regulations and provide additional enforcement mechanisms\n\n3. Key Provisions:\n- Criminalizing financial transactions designed to conceal illegal proceeds\n- Requiring financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Establishing penalties including fines and imprisonment\n- Mandating reporting of cash transactions over $10,000\n\n4. International Cooperation:\n- The U.S. works with international organizations like FATF (Financial Action Task Force)\n- Participates in global efforts to prevent money laundering\n\nThese statutes provide comprehensive legal frameworks for preventing, detecting, and prosecuting money laundering activities across various sectors and jurisdictions.",
